    <title>Test Article</title>
   <section>
      <title>Core Constructs</title>
      <para>We can have paragraphs of text but we already had that.  Without an additional CSS, we
         can get ordered and itemized lists to work as well as titles, figures, etc.  That gives the
         browser a default to work with and the reader a basic fallback.</para>
      <para>The user can then put into the document their own customizations of the layout just as
         they regularly would do.  The do this through the regular method of putting an HTML
            <code>link</code> element within the header.</para>
      <section>
         <title>Supported Elements</title>
         <para>Here is a list of elements that are supported:</para>
         <itemizedlist>
            <listitem>
               <para>article</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>code</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>figure</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>itemizedlist</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>listitem</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>programlisting</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>title</para>
            </listitem>
            <listitem>
               <para>xref (Example: <xref linkend="pan-ex"/>)</para>
            </listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
      </section>
      <section>
         <title>Known Issues</title>
         <para>Of what has been attempted, none.  Of course, I haven't gotten that many elements working.</para>
      </section>
      <section>
         <title>Getting the Code</title>
         <para>The code and examples are available in the <link
               xlink:href="https://github.com/alexmilowski/db-component">db-component</link>
            project.</para>
      </section>
   </section>
